---
// src/pages/press/index.astro
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  door="press"
  title="The Missing Story"
  description="The argument for the skinny union: why traditional labor stalled, and the strongest objection to the model, answered on the merits."
>

  <!-- ── Door Hero — Sober Register ────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="door-hero door-hero--press" aria-label="The Argument door">
      <p class="door-hero-eyebrow">The Argument</p>
      <h1 class="door-hero-headline">
        The <em>missing story</em> in American labor.
      </h1>
      <div class="door-hero-rule"></div>
      <p class="door-hero-sub">
        The legal architecture exists. The labor market analysis is documented. The workers
        are there. The union has not been built &mdash; until now.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Argument I: Where Labor Stalled ──────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Where labor stalled">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Argument I</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Where Labor Stalled</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>Traditional labor is stalled because its focus is off.</h2>

        <p>
          There are a lot of non-union employers with humane human resources practices, with
          fair employee handbooks, with reasonable disciplinary practices, with engaging
          professional development opportunities, and with flexible attitudes around schedules
          and remote work.
        </p>

        <p>
          But there are no employers who will voluntarily pay workers as much as they can
          afford to.
        </p>

        <blockquote class="pull-quote">
          The boss is probably not Henry Clay Frick. But neither is she Santa Claus.
        </blockquote>

        <p>
          And yet traditional unions continue to offer a package that devotes limited
          bargaining power to the first set of issues rather than just focusing on pay. The
          untold story in labor today is the failure of imagination in the labor movement to
          proactively adjust this package to reach new classes of employees.
        </p>

        <p>
          What those workers have not been offered is a union that concentrates entirely on
          compensation and benefits. It would be a simpler model, an easier sell, a more
          immediate and meaningful improvement for the employees.
        </p>

        <p>
          We call it the skinny union. It has been achievable under existing law all along.
          But the workers who would benefit don&rsquo;t know this, and the &ldquo;full
          fat&rdquo; unions have no incentive to tell them. Their package is built around job
          security and negotiated work rules &mdash; and every ounce of leverage spent on
          those items is leverage not spent on pay.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Argument II: The Practitioners' Objection ─────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The practitioners' objection">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Argument II</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">The Practitioners&rsquo; Objection</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>Experienced labor practitioners discount it &mdash; why?</h2>

        <p>
          They think workers won&rsquo;t hold the focus on wages. They think they&rsquo;ll
          disperse their energy into other issues &mdash; job security, seniority, grievance
          procedures. They think it is a question of politics.
        </p>

        <p>
          Their prediction runs as follows. Worker organizations are inevitably captured by
          their most motivated constituency. The members who organize most intensely, sustain
          engagement over time, participate most actively in governance, and ultimately drive
          bargaining priorities are those facing the most acute personal risk. A worker who
          fears discipline or termination has a strong, immediate, personal stake in the
          union&rsquo;s agenda; a worker who would prefer higher wages but is performing well
          and has outside options has a weaker, more diffuse one.
        </p>

        <p>
          Over time, the dynamics of internal governance favor the motivated over the mobile.
          Even if the founding cohort is a group of strong performers whose primary concern is
          compensation, the workers who stay most engaged &mdash; who show up to meetings, run
          for office, care most about the next contract &mdash; will increasingly be those
          facing employment-security concerns. The union&rsquo;s bargaining mandate drifts,
          through member politics rather than formal amendment, toward the protections those
          members need.
        </p>

        <p>
          They might be right. But we think this prediction comes from experience negotiating
          on behalf of and against existing unions. In each of those negotiations the
          bargaining unit is starting with a &ldquo;full fat&rdquo; CBA package. The politics
          of trading existing non-pay benefits for more pay is obviously difficult. And it is
          obviously different from a bargaining unit that forms explicitly just to focus on
          pay. Whether a group of employees who aim for a simple goal can hold that focus is
          just a different proposition.
        </p>

        <blockquote class="pull-quote">
          They&rsquo;ve never seen that resolve for a reason: it has never been on the menu.
        </blockquote>

        <p>
          And the resolve of the founders of a skinny union has structural protection during
          the first term of the CBA. A multi-year, formal agreement to bargain only over wages
          and benefits is not undone by a motivated minority pushing for grievance procedures
          six months in. Reopening scope requires the employer&rsquo;s agreement. The
          model&rsquo;s legal architecture is not a norm to drift from. It is a contract term
          to renegotiate. That changes the internal politics considerably. Or rather, it
          ensures that there is sufficient time for the benefits of the approach to
          materialize and prove its value &mdash; and support the resolve to remain focused.
        </p>

        <p>
          Or, not. It is certainly possible that after four years the bargaining unit (or a
          loud minority) will decide that it is worth trading pay for job security. But the
          CBA term ensures that the decision will be based on meaningful experience of the
          benefits of the skinny union rather than mere talk. Furthermore, any move to seek
          changes to non-pay items in the second CBA negotiation is likely to result in a very
          stark pay trade-off in order to buy those changes.
        </p>

        <p>
          But, really, speculation like this only goes so far (not very). Ultimately, it is an
          empirical question. Traditional unions are only offering &ldquo;full fat&rdquo;
          models. The skinny union is possible, but has never been tried. Meanwhile, barely 6%
          of private sector employees are union members. Something new needs to be tried.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── For Press ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Press resources">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Resources</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">For Press</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>For reporters and editors.</h2>
        <div class="placeholder">
          <span class="placeholder-label">Coming &mdash; Press Kit</span>
          <p>
            The advocacy publication (full argument), quotable framings, background on the legal
            architecture, and contact information. Available on request in the interim.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>
